         <abstract>
            <p>Utility issues have attraction as possible substitutes for long-term bonds in employee benefit accounts. They supply greatly improved protection of purchasing power with a minimal increase in risk to dollar income and dollar value of principal. The historic superiority of utility commons to bonds can be demonstrated by comparing the discounted present values of income streams and capital changes for the two types of issues. It can also be shown that utilities should outperform bonds on this basis if present, relatively low, price/earnings ratios hold, or alternately that utilities could keep pace with bonds despite significant P/E ratio attrition.</p>
          </abstract>
